local Tags = {
  cloning_source = "cloning_source"
}

--[[ Lua code. See documentation: https://api.tabletopsimulator.com/ --]]

--[[ The onLoad event is called after the game save finishes loading. --]]
function onLoad()
    --[[ print('onLoad!') --]]
end

--[[ The onUpdate event is called once per frame. --]]
function onUpdate()

end

function onObjectPickUp(colorName, object)
  if object.hasTag(Tags.cloning_source) then
    executeCloning(object)
  end
end

function executeCloning(object)
  local clone = object.clone()
  clone.setPosition(object.getPosition())
  clone.addTag(Tags.cloning_source)
  object.removeTag(Tags.cloning_source)
end

ObjectStates.Name: Custom_Tile
ObjectStates.LuaScript:
denomination = 50

function onSpawn()
  setChipValue(self)
  -- Global.call("setChipValue", self)
end

function onLoad()
  -- Global.call("setChipValue", self)
  setChipValue(self)
end

function setChipValue(object)
  local denomination = object.getVar("denomination")
  local quantity = object.getQuantity()
  local value = denomination

  if quantity == -1 then
    object.setDescription("")
  else
    value = denomination*quantity
    object.setDescription(denomination .. "*" .. quantity .. " = " .. value)
  end

  object.setVar("value", value)
end

ObjectStates.LuaScript:
function onLoad()
  math.randomseed(os.time())
  self.addContextMenuItem("Roll", roll)
end

function roll(player_color, position, object)
  self.addForce(vector(0, 20, 0))
  -- Use random generated torgue is wrong way. By unclear reason random generated torgue almost always leads to roll same face.
  changeFace = math.random() > 0.5
  if (changeFace)
  then
  self.addTorque(vector(0.42, 0.16, 0.33))
  else
    self.addTorque(vector(0.52, 0.48, 0.93))
  end
end
